			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="114">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I admire Katherine LaBelle&rsquo;s courage in sharing her experience of sexual abuse [&ldquo;<a href="/article/4982">A Boy&rsquo;s Girl</a>,&rdquo; October 2014]. I want her to know that her words helped me heal. One part in particular touched my heart. LaBelle describes talking to a woman with an abusive boyfriend: &ldquo;I tell her it wasn&rsquo;t her fault, that there was nothing she could have done to deserve it. I tell her this not because it&rsquo;s what I am supposed to say, but because it is true. I wonder, in that moment, why I never thought to say it to myself.&rdquo;</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Colleen Nolan Armstrong<br>Naperville, Illinois</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="389">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I love <em>The Sun</em> and take it<span class="smallcaps"> </span>with me to the gym to read while I&rsquo;m on the stairclimber. The magazine is so engrossing that the time, which otherwise seems endless, whips right by.</p>

<p>I was a magazine editor for twenty-five years before I retired, and, like any longtime editor, I have my share of pet peeves. I can&rsquo;t count all the uses of <em>over</em> I&rsquo;ve changed to <em>more than</em>. Since I retired, the <em>Chicago Manual of Style</em> has decided that the two are interchangeable. So I&rsquo;ve given up on that one, but I still have a huge problem with the use of <em>myself</em> in place of <em>me</em> or <em>I</em>. So imagine my distress when I read the sentence &ldquo;There is no one to act as a barrier between my father and myself&rdquo; in &ldquo;<a href="/articles/4982">A Boy&rsquo;s Girl</a>,&rdquo; by Katherine LaBelle [October 2014]. It should be &ldquo;my father and me.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I know it&rsquo;s a minor point and hardly worth mentioning, but I&rsquo;m concerned that, if I read more such errors, I might miss a step on the stairclimber and hurt myself.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Chris Petty<br>New Westminster, British Columbia<br />Canada</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

